SW,<br><br>
I liked the last sentence a few posts up, where you state that we (vets) don't need to look to others for what we can give ourselves.<br><br>
If we truly believe that, then how important are any acts of contrition? By anyone? Should they matter?<br><br>
It has been much easier for me (to forgive) because I was not a believer in the war. However, I am a believer in the soldier who went to fight. It boils down to being able to separate the two. <br><br>
It is becoming more evident that those who remain staunch believers in the war will forever maintain a sense of bitterness towards the protestors. I am a combat vet. The stakes were high. So, I have resigned myself to the fact that there will always be the great divide between many of our citizens. I give up.<br><br>
Allow me to ask a rhetorical question. Is it ok for returning vets to spit on those whom they claimed spit on them? Check out thread #20. I just did last nite. I give up.<br><br>
It is with a tremendous sense of relief (for me) that I have what Class Lass refers to as a &quot;gift&quot; of forgiveness. I was sent out on missions with inexperienced officers. We were sent to die. It didn't occur to me at the time that many times our ground forces were the &quot;bait&quot;. Throw in the many deaths and injuries from booby traps and friendly fire incidents and my recollection is a witches brew of nightmares and intrusive thoughts. I thank the merciful God, whom I blasphened in those days, for sparing me the nightmares during my sleeptime. Bitter? How could I be when the God who saved my neck, commands &quot;Love One another&quot;? Unconditionally. Without conditions. Regardless of anything.<br><br>
The answer lies in vets supporting other vets, yet the most sublime state of mind is for us to be generous. I think that we all have the capability.<br><br>

